In Paraguay, there are few sexual and reproductive healthcare resources to aid and protect women, especially young women and poor women, from the hardships of pregnancy, specifically unplanned and unwanted pregnancies. There are a lack of sexual education resources and access to birth control facilities (for instance, contraception pills). Naturally, the underlying problem is the funding that the government cannot provide for its people about parenthood. Our project seeks to provide young, suburban women of low income with education and workshops on sex, human development, and more – this could pair with tourism bottles to offer women more avenues for knowledge, dialogue, and resources from our project to aid them on their journey.

The community-based Paraguayan women news program “Mujeres en Red,” whose target audience is primarily young women, has discussed topics such as domestic violence, reproductive health, abortion, teen pregnancy, premarital sex, and more. Many women in Paraguay discuss and recognize importance of improving reproductive health and sex education concerning contraception, sexually transmitted infections, and more – and they want these conditions to improve, but the question is, what do the resources look like in practice? Where do women go for these resources?

Human Trafficking

Our project seeks to improve and reform women’s safety and boost tourism in the capital of Paraguay – one sector of our project will include education and workshops on human trafficking and ways to identify and distinguish situations of exploitation from jobs. Paraguay
